AGi - Norway, Ireland and Spain will recognize the Palestinian State from 28 May, sparking the joy of Palestinian leaders and triggering the fury of Israel. The three nations hope that other countries will follow the example, but Europe remains divided on the question, with France who has already said without means terms that this is not the time to grant recognition. The announcement by the first Norwegian ministers Jonas Gahr Store, > Spanish Pedro Sanchez e> Irish Simon Harris > is the second diplomatic strike this week, after the prosecutor of the International Criminal Court asked <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-20/corte-aja-chiede-stop-netanyahu-leader-hamas-per-crimini Israel reacted immediately recalling its ambassadors in the three nations and defining the move a "premio on terrorism".
&nbsp;
<
<div </div
</div
&nbsp;
According to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Tel Aviv it is likely to transform the countries protagonists of the move into "a pawn in the hands of Iran>, feeding extremism and instability". The Middle Eastern question is "historically what has created more divisions in Europe": That is why, according to the ambassador of Israel in Italy, Alon Bar>, recognition risks "to weaken its role in the realization of a peace process and the solution of the two States". Tel Aviv's diplomatic representative acknowledged that "it is still too early to understand the impact" that this choice will have on the ongoing conflict and relations between countries. But, he added, "it is not enough to recognize a state because it exists" and perhaps today's announcements have the purpose of "promoting the creation of a Palestinian State". In any case, for Bar there is at the moment "especially a negative impact on Europe's ability to play an important role" in the region.
&nbsp;
For its part, the Organization for the Liberation of Palestine (Olp) hailed the move as "historical" and Hamas praised what defined an "important step" result of the "corrupt resistance" of the Palestinians. Slovenia and Malta are expected to join the nous of the countries that recognize Palestine. Moreover, announcing the recognition, some leaders publicly condemned the Israeli leadership. According to Sanchez, for example, with its "dolore and destruction" policy in the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-01-15/terrorist-raanana-centro-israele-ostaggi-ultime-notizie-24845133/"> Gaza strategy</a> Israeli premier Benjamin Netahu solution. The Turkish Government expressed satisfaction and promised to intensify diplomatic efforts to convince other countries to make the same decision. Jordan defines the move as an "important and essential step towards the solution of the two States with an independent and sovereign Palestinian state within the borders of 4 June 1967". The Foreign Minister Safadi also accused the Israeli government not only of rejecting the solution of the two states, of adopting "concrete measures on the field that are killing the chances of reaching peace in the region".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
For Saudi Arabia, the move confirms "the international consensus on the intrinsic right of the Palestinian people to self-determination". The European front is disaligned. The Slovenian government announced that it will soon join the recognition of the Palestinian state and Prime Minister Robert Golob said he wanted to "contribute reform and strengthen the Palestinian government", supporting the formula of the two states which, in his words, "someone sees as a solution to lasting peace". Belgium takes time: "Our priority, at this time, is to see how we can free the hostages and how we can get an immediate ceasefire," said Prime Minister Alexander De Croo, > "recognition must be a lever to achieve results for the people of Palestine. The discussion must take place, but must take place in this perspective" The White House rejects the move of Spain, Ireland and Norway, stating that a two-state solution should be achieved through diplomatic negotiations. A spokesman for the National Security Council stated that Joe Biden believes that "a Palestinian state should be reached through direct negotiations between the parties, not through unilateral recognition."
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
In Italy the opposition asks that the government follow the example of Spain, Ireland and Norway. "It must also do Italy" writes the leader of the M5s, Giuseppe Conte, "Invece Tajani explains that Italy looks at what the majority does in the G7 and follows it. This is the Meloni government. There's nothing else to add." "We need an effort from the European Union and for this reason we ask for the European recognition of the state of Palestine" says the secretary Pd, Elly Schlein, "The solution of two peoples two states for us remains the one to point to". But, while a state of Israel is already there and has the right to exist in peace and security, it still lacks, unfortunately and guiltyly, the recognition of the other state, that of Palestine." &nbsp;&nbsp;
